\pard\plain \sb360\ql\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs28\b1 Exegetical Notes to Book 6, Act 2, Scene 3}
\par\pard\plain \sb180\qc\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs24\b1 Incident One: Announcement of Isaac\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92s Birth (18:1\endash 15)}
\par\plain {\f2\fs24\b1\i1 Appearance of Divine Visitors (18:1\endash 2)}
\par\pard\plain \fi360\sb180\ql\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b1 1. appeared.}{\f0\fs24  To \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93appear\u8221\'94 and \u8220\'93see\u8221\'94 is a key of this scene (18:1, 2 [2x], 21; see also 19:1, 28).}
\par\pard\plain \fi360\ql\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b1 The }{\f0\fs24\b1\scaps Lord}{\f0\fs24\b1  appeared.}{\f0\fs24  With the Lord\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s return appearance (see 17:1), he confirms his revelation of 17:19 and declares certain and swift fulfillment. This appearance also clearly identifies Abraham as a prophet who is given foreknowledge of God\u8217\'92s plans and judgments.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b1 great trees of Mamre.}{\f0\fs24  See 13:18; 14:13.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b1 entrance to his tent.}{\f0\fs24  Contrast this with 19:1. Abraham sits in the shade of a sojourner\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s tent, a welcoming place to travelers; Lot will sit at the gate of an evil city, hazardous to strangers who enter.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b1 heat of the day.}{\f0\fs24  Abraham lives by his subjective experience of the day\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s downy light, noon-day heat, and cool evening breeze, not by hours and minutes. During the heat of the day travelers seek shade and rest. Abraham does not appear inconvenienced by the interruption of his siesta or by the labor he must do in the day\u8217\'92s heat.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b1 2. three men.}{\f0\fs24  This is actually the Lord and two angels (see 18:1, 10; 19:1). The later identifications of the \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93men\u8221\'94 (18:10, 13, 16\endash 17, 33; 19:1) confirm their manifest difference. One man is none other than the Lord, as 18:2\endash 3 and especially 10, 13\endash 15 make explicit. However, the Lord and his heavenly assembly in their incarnation appear in human form (see 16:7).}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b1 standing nearby.}{\f0\fs24  The narrator describes the oriental equivalent of knocking at the door.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b1 When he saw them, he hurried.}{\f0\fs24  Abraham\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s rush to welcome his guests is immediate.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b1 bowed low to the ground.}{\f0\fs24  Abraham\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s address, \u8220\'93my }{\f0\fs24\scaps Lord}{\f0\fs24 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8221\'94 (see below) and his reference to himself as \u8220\'93your servant\u8221\'94 are accompanied with an appropriate gesture of awe and humility (18:3).\{\\Scrv_fn=}{\f3\fs24\b0\i0  Waltke, B. K., & Fredricks, C. J. (2001). \\end_Scrv_fn\}\{\\Scrv_fn=}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://ref.ly/logosres/genesiswaltke?ref=Bible.Ge18.1-33&off=3779"}{\fldrslt\f4\fs24\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf3 Genesis: a commentary\\end_Scrv_fn\}\{\\Scrv_fn=}}{\f3\fs24\b0\i0  (pp. 266\endash 267). Grand Rapids, MI: Zondervan.\\end_Scrv_fn\}}
\par\plain \f0\fs24
\par\pard\plain \sb360\qc\ltrch\loch {\f2\fs24\b1\i1 Abraham\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8217\'92s Hospitality (18:3\endash 8)}
\par\pard\plain \fi360\sb180\ql\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b1 3. found favor.}{\f0\fs24  This is always spoken to one of higher rank.}
\par\pard\plain \fi360\ql\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b1 my lord.}{\f0\fs24  This is better translated \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93my }{\f0\fs24\scaps Lord}{\f0\fs24 .\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8221\'94 The translation \u8220\'93my lord\u8221\'94 is misleading, since the Hebrew text refers to a title for God. }{\f0\fs24\scaps niv}{\f0\fs24  translates the same Hebrew in 18:27 as \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93the Lord\u8221\'94 (see 18:1, 13, 17), although it should be written in upper case. Abraham addresses \u8220\'93the }{\f0\fs24\scaps Lord}{\f0\fs24 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8221\'94 (singular) in 18:3 and all three men (plural) in 18:4\endash 5.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b1 your servant.}{\f0\fs24  The consummate host offers himself humbly.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b1 4\endash 5. wash your feet \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8230\'85 rest \u8230\'85 eat \u8230\'85 refreshed.}{\f0\fs24  Abraham attends to all his guests\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92 unspoken needs.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b1 6\endash 7. hurried \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8230\'85 Quick \u8230\'85 ran \u8230\'85 hurried.}{\f0\fs24  The narrator creates an intimate picture of Abraham, the consummate host, rushing to prepare a great feast for his guests. Throughout the story Abraham is completely at their service.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b1 6. seahs.}{\f0\fs24  A seah is two gallons (eight liters) of a grain.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b1 fine flour.}{\f0\fs24  Given the rapid preparation of Abraham\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s meal, it is likely that he also offered bread without yeast, but the narrator blanks this fact to feature Abraham\u8217\'92s bread made of fine flour in contrast with Lot\u8217\'92s bread made without yeast (see 19:3).}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b1 7\endash 8. choice, tender calf \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8230\'85 curds and milk.}{\f0\fs24  Abraham\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s offering of \u8220\'93something to eat\u8221\'94 turns out to be a royal banquet. In the ancient Near East, goat\u8217\'92s milk was especially prized because of its energy and easy digestibility.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b1 8. While they ate.}{\f0\fs24  The narrator slows the story from action to dialogue. The initiative passes to the strangers, specifically to \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93the }{\f0\fs24\scaps Lord}{\f0\fs24 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8221\'94 as the prime speaker.\{\\Scrv_fn=}{\f3\fs24\b0\i0  Waltke, B. K., & Fredricks, C. J. (2001). \\end_Scrv_fn\}\{\\Scrv_fn=}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://ref.ly/logosres/genesiswaltke?ref=Bible.Ge18.3-8&off=914"}{\fldrslt\f4\fs24\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf3 Genesis: a commentary\\end_Scrv_fn\}\{\\Scrv_fn=}}{\f3\fs24\b0\i0  (p. 267). Grand Rapids, MI: Zondervan.\\end_Scrv_fn\}}
