\par\pard\plain \sb360\qc\ltrch\loch {\f2\fs24\b1\i1 Annunciation of Isaac\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8217\'92s Birth (18:9\endash 15)}
\par\pard\plain \fi360\sb180\ql\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b1 9. Where.}{\f0\fs24  This is a rhetorical question, since the Lord knew what Sarah was doing behind him (see 18:13\endash 15). The question conveys the Lord\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s concern and secures Sarah\u8217\'92s attention for the announcement.}
\par\pard\plain \fi360\ql\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b1 10. I will surely return.}{\f0\fs24  This is a clear indication that the speaker is the Lord, since he alone can faithfully promise life out of barrenness and decay.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b1 about this time next year.}{\f0\fs24  The promise (15:4) and covenant (17:16\endash 21) is now escalated to a precise time.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b1 Sarah \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8230\'85 son.}{\f0\fs24  God makes a promise demanding faith (see below, \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93God\u8217\'92s Promise and Faith\u8221\'94 in the Theological Reflections).}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b1 11. past the age of childbearing.}{\f0\fs24  The Hebrew literally reads, \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Sarah no longer experienced the cycle of women.\u8221\'94 Her body is procreatively dead (see Rom. 4:19; Heb. 11:11\endash 12; see also \u8220\'93God\u8217\'92s Promise and Faith\u8221\'94 below).}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b1 12. Sarah laughed.}{\f0\fs24  Both Abraham and Sarah first laugh unbelievingly at God\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s promises (see 17:17).}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b1 my master.}{\f0\fs24  See 1 Peter 3:6. Sarah understands her social identity and significance in her relationship to Abraham.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b1 pleasure.}{\f0\fs24  This is a unique Hebrew term, of uncertain meaning, translated \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93conception\u8221\'94 by an ancient Aramaic translation, \u8220\'93lust\u8221\'94 by }{\f0\fs24\i1 HALOT}{\f0\fs24 ,}{\f0\fs24\super 144}{\f0\fs24  and \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93delight\u8221\'94 by J. D. Price. Abraham and Sarah have accepted barrenness as normal.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b1 13\endash 14. Why did Sarah laugh \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8230\'85 is anything too hard.}{\f0\fs24  As assurance of his miraculous power, the Lord verbalizes Sarah\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s secret thoughts. His rhetorical question declares that, since he is God, everything is possible (see 15:4\endash 6; Heb. 11:11; cf. Jer. 32:17; Mark 10:27; Luke 1:37).}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b1 15. lied.}{\f0\fs24  The Bible does not gloss over the sins of its hero and heroine of faith (cf. 12:13).}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b1 you did laugh.}{\f0\fs24  This is both a restorative rebuke (Prov. 28:13) and an assuring sign: the one who reads her thoughts can open her womb.\{\\Scrv_fn=}{\f3\fs24\b0\i0  Waltke, B. K., & Fredricks, C. J. (2001). \\end_Scrv_fn\}\{\\Scrv_fn=}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://ref.ly/logosres/genesiswaltke?ref=Bible.Ge18.9-15&off=1053"}{\fldrslt\f4\fs24\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf3 Genesis: a commentary\\end_Scrv_fn\}\{\\Scrv_fn=}}{\f3\fs24\b0\i0  (pp. 267\endash 268). Grand Rapids, MI: Zondervan.\\end_Scrv_fn\}}
